# SYNC Intent

**Portable Human Authorization**

App Store • OpenVerifier • Local-First • Independent Verification

---

## Abstract

SYNC is a local-first reference implementation for portable human-authorization receipts.

The project demonstrates how human intent, review evidence, device authorization, time, policy context, and cryptographic integrity can be preserved inside a portable evidence artifact that remains independently verifiable outside the originating application.

Unlike traditional workflow systems that retain approval records inside operator-controlled databases, SYNC produces portable receipts that travel with the decision itself.

Receipts are created entirely on-device, exported directly by the owner, and verified independently through an open verification implementation.

No account.

No cloud custody.

No vendor-controlled verification service.

---

# Design Goals

SYNC is designed around six engineering goals.

### G1 — Portable Human Authorization

Authorization evidence should survive application boundaries.

Receipts are designed to remain useful independently of the software that originally created them.

---

### G2 — Local-First Custody

Receipt generation should not require cloud infrastructure.

Human authorization occurs entirely on the user's device.

Evidence remains under user control unless intentionally shared.

---

### G3 — Independent Verification

Receipt verification should not require trust in the issuing application.

Any relying party should be able to independently evaluate cryptographic integrity using open verification software.

---

### G4 — Cryptographic Integrity

Visible receipt contents must remain bound to the exact signed canonical payload.

Verification fails whenever signed receipt contents have been altered.

---

### G5 — Interoperability

Human authorization evidence should compose with external authorization and execution systems without modifying either system's trust model.

SYNC intentionally separates presentation evidence from execution authority, allowing independently verified receipt systems to bind to the same underlying action through cryptographic digest relationships while preserving independent trust roots.

---

### G6 — Human Readability

Receipts should remain understandable by both software and people.

Cryptographic evidence should support legal, operational, and compliance review without requiring protocol expertise.

---

# Trust Model

SYNC intentionally separates independent trust questions.

• What was reviewed?

• What evidence was presented?

• What authorization occurred?

• Can those claims be independently verified?

Receipt generation and receipt verification are intentionally separated.

Applications create receipts.

OpenVerifier verifies receipts.

Neither component requires centralized cloud custody.

